<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-06-05T09:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-06-05T09:00:00-05:00" n="318" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d318">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">724.3415/3797: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul at Geneva</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gilbert</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Geneva</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-06-05T15:00:00+01:00">June 5, 1934—3
                                    p.m.</date><lb/>[Received June 5—11:35 a.m.]</dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>136. Arms embargo. Consulate’s 135, June 5,2 p.m., paragraph 3. I
                                have been privately informed that a meeting of “interested states”
                                was also considered with thought being given to possible American
                                participation. There have been no outward developments in this
                                whatsoever and I have heard no discussion of it.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Gilbert</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>